    <section id="id1168442528702">


      <title>Structure</title>
      <para id="id1168442771013">The nitrogen atoms in hydrazine adopt sp<sup>3</sup> hybridization (<link target-id="id9010420"/>a), and molecule adopts a <emphasis effect="italics">gauche</emphasis> conformation in the vapor, liquid and solid states (<link target-id="id9010420"/>b). </para>

      <figure id="id9010420">
        <media id="id9010420_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics7-fb45.jpg" id="id9010420__onlineimage" width="300" print-width="2.5in"/>
        </media>
<caption>The structure of hydrazine. </caption>
      </figure>



      <para id="id1168442734635">In a similar manner to ammonia, <link target-id="eip-22225"/>, hydrazine is a self-ionizing, <link target-id="eip-22226"/>. While there is a wide range of salts of the N<sub>2</sub>H<sub>5</sub><sup>+</sup> cation, only the sodium and potassium salts of N<sub>2</sub>H<sub>3</sub><sup>-</sup> are stable. </para>

<equation id="eip-22225"> <media id="id1168437342125_media" alt="">
